00:13:46.960 --> 00:13:48.760
JUSSI LAAKKONEN: That actually
captures the game play.

00:13:48.760 --> 00:13:53.760
And then we have our server side
which runs on a Note GS

00:13:53.760 --> 00:13:57.400
Mobile DB on the various
service and CDNs.

00:13:57.400 --> 00:14:00.470
And basically, that's where the
videos are uploaded to.

00:14:00.470 --> 00:14:04.220
And the whole social interface
you saw is all HTML5.

00:14:04.220 --> 00:14:06.775
So there is no separate
Everyplay app right now.

00:14:06.775 --> 00:14:09.750
It's all HTML5, all the social
stuff we looked at.

00:14:09.750 --> 00:14:15.840
And we provide that on desktop
browsers, mobile browsers as

00:14:15.840 --> 00:14:18.620
we looked at within Facebook
within Twitter.

00:14:18.620 --> 00:14:19.450
JAREK WILKIEWICZ: Oh, great.

00:14:19.450 --> 00:14:21.050
JUSSI LAAKKONEN: And then we
provide integration to

00:14:21.050 --> 00:14:24.630
services like YouTube where
we upload the video.

00:14:24.630 --> 00:14:27.610
It's always uploaded to the
user's own account on YouTube.

00:14:27.610 --> 00:14:29.370
So we want the users
to be stars.

00:14:29.370 --> 00:14:32.355
And so they can have them
on their own channels.

00:14:32.355 --> 00:14:32.760
JAREK WILKIEWICZ: Yeah.

00:14:32.760 --> 00:14:36.060
Yeah, this is definitely the
approach that we recommend.

00:14:36.060 --> 00:14:39.850
We also find that these videos
are more likely to go viral

00:14:39.850 --> 00:14:42.100
because users have an incentive
to actually share

00:14:42.100 --> 00:14:42.710
their achievements.

00:14:42.710 --> 00:14:45.640
So this fits the use
case quite well.

00:14:45.640 --> 00:14:49.110
So how do you use
the YouTube API?

00:14:49.110 --> 00:14:49.260
JUSSI LAAKKONEN: Excuse me.

00:14:49.260 --> 00:14:50.820
You were breaking up a little.

00:14:50.820 --> 00:14:53.160
JAREK WILKIEWICZ: My question
was, how do you use the

00:14:53.160 --> 00:14:53.850
YouTube API?

00:14:53.850 --> 00:14:57.320
Can you tell a bit more
about how you use it?

00:14:57.320 --> 00:14:59.100
JUSSI LAAKKONEN: So we have
a server-to-server

00:14:59.100 --> 00:15:00.150
connection to YouTube.

00:15:00.150 --> 00:15:02.530
So we use that for--

00:15:02.530 --> 00:15:08.150
first, the user authenticates
himself with OAuth2 to

00:15:08.150 --> 00:15:10.150
authenticate that he has
a YouTube account

00:15:10.150 --> 00:15:11.100
and ability to publish.

00:15:11.100 --> 00:15:13.900
And we store that access
keys after that.

00:15:13.900 --> 00:15:17.320
And as we have the video on
the server, we use our

00:15:17.320 --> 00:15:19.950
server-to-server integration to
YouTube service to upload

00:15:19.950 --> 00:15:23.120
the video after it's been
encoded on our service.

00:15:23.120 --> 00:15:23.470
JAREK WILKIEWICZ: Got it.

00:15:23.470 --> 00:15:25.650
So the token is obtained
on the client.

00:15:25.650 --> 00:15:29.140
So this is something that the
OAuth flow is executed on the

00:15:29.140 --> 00:15:30.530
mobile device.

00:15:30.530 --> 00:15:34.130
And then the refresh token is
sent to the server side.

00:15:34.130 --> 00:15:37.730
And then the video is uploaded
on behalf of the user using an

00:15:37.730 --> 00:15:40.460
access token that is obtained
from the refresh token that

00:15:40.460 --> 00:15:42.550
you have actually obtained
on the client.

00:15:42.550 --> 00:15:43.430
Is that correct?

00:15:43.430 --> 00:15:43.806
JUSSI LAAKKONEN: Correct.

00:15:43.806 --> 00:15:44.560
That's correct.

00:15:44.560 --> 00:15:44.815
JAREK WILKIEWICZ: OK.

00:15:44.815 --> 00:15:47.330
JUSSI LAAKKONEN: And we don't
directly uploaded from a

00:15:47.330 --> 00:15:48.730
client to YouTube because
we also do

00:15:48.730 --> 00:15:50.890
moderation on these videos.

00:15:50.890 --> 00:15:53.710
And we have certain safeguards
in place to make sure that the

00:15:53.710 --> 00:15:56.670
content is PG-13, if you will.

00:15:56.670 --> 00:15:59.600
And that's why we do the
re-encoding on the server side

00:15:59.600 --> 00:16:01.780
and the security checks on the
server side and then upload

00:16:01.780 --> 00:16:02.810
from the service.

00:16:02.810 --> 00:16:05.490
This also means that the user,
if he is sharing to multiple

00:16:05.490 --> 00:16:07.950
services, he only needs
to upload once.

00:16:07.950 --> 00:16:09.900
And as we provide a
services-like background

00:16:09.900 --> 00:16:13.450
uploading, then the video upload
will complete even if

00:16:13.450 --> 00:16:16.360
the user exits the
application.

00:16:16.360 --> 00:16:16.720
JAREK WILKIEWICZ: Great.

00:16:16.720 --> 00:16:21.320
And then are you using YouTube
API v2 or v3 for the upload?

00:16:21.320 --> 00:16:22.700
JUSSI LAAKKONEN: We're currently
using version two.

00:16:22.700 --> 00:16:25.010
But we're very excited by the
opportunity that version 3 is

00:16:25.010 --> 00:16:25.370
opening up.

00:16:25.370 --> 00:16:28.430
So we're very much looking
forward to migrating to that.

00:16:28.430 --> 00:16:32.250
And we have big plans to
leverage the data API on

00:16:32.250 --> 00:16:34.180
YouTube because I think there
are great things you can build

00:16:34.180 --> 00:16:37.430
with that, play lists, do a
feature that kind of creates

00:16:37.430 --> 00:16:38.790
the content of your channel.

00:16:38.790 --> 00:16:40.880
And we're really on the
early stages of that.

00:16:40.880 --> 00:16:43.740
We first wanted to enable
the sharing for players.

00:16:43.740 --> 00:16:46.120
And now the next step is kind of
creating that content into

00:16:46.120 --> 00:16:49.260
interesting playlists,
organizing that by games, and

00:16:49.260 --> 00:16:51.230
enabling games to find
their audiences.

00:16:51.230 --> 00:16:54.990
So we're excited about the
new version three API.

00:16:54.990 --> 00:16:55.290
JAREK WILKIEWICZ: Great.

00:16:55.290 --> 00:16:58.160
And I think the YouTube audience
will appreciate easy

00:16:58.160 --> 00:17:01.180
way to find this content,
especially if you're talking

00:17:01.180 --> 00:17:02.070
about [? queue ration ?]

00:17:02.070 --> 00:17:02.810
and play list management.

00:17:02.810 --> 00:17:05.310
I think that's all very
important for game developers.

00:17:05.310 --> 00:17:08.220
Because once the content is
out there, how do you help

00:17:08.220 --> 00:17:09.010
users find it?

00:17:09.010 --> 00:17:10.250
And definitely the
[? queue ration ?]

00:17:10.250 --> 00:17:12.700
is the right way
to approach it.

00:17:12.700 --> 00:17:15.010
JUSSI LAAKKONEN: We also
leverage metadata so our

00:17:15.010 --> 00:17:19.800
developers can specify a number
of arrivals, some

00:17:19.800 --> 00:17:24.510
public, some private, that's
used to navigate these videos.

00:17:24.510 --> 00:17:28.580
And we also are publishing I
think most of that, if not

00:17:28.580 --> 00:17:29.800
all, to YouTube.

00:17:29.800 --> 00:17:34.450
And the goal is to really enable
rich search abilities

00:17:34.450 --> 00:17:36.170
within YouTube.

00:17:36.170 --> 00:17:37.080
JAREK WILKIEWICZ: Great.

00:17:37.080 --> 00:17:40.510
So one question that I typically
like to ask is,

00:17:40.510 --> 00:17:43.410
while you were developing
